North Central device distribution is on July 23 and 24 from 9 a.m. to 6p.m. Freshmen and seniors are encouraged to come on July 23 and sophomores and juniors are encouraged to come on July 24. Regardless of need, ALL North Central students should have a district issued device during the school year. We also ask that you return any old devices you have from last year. All cars will be directed to enter campus from the East entrance.

You can speed up the Chromebook check-out process by placing a sheet of paper with the students name and ID# in the window of your car.

post_text: Lights on For Justice: On Friday, June 19 stadium lights across Marion County will be turned on for 8 minutes 46 seconds as a tribute to George Floyd. Mr. Floyd was born on October 14 therefore the lights on will start at 10:14 PM. June 19, otherwise known as Juneteenth, was chosen because of the date significance to the African American community. Juneteenth, also called as Freedom Day, Jubilee Day, or Celebration Day is an American holiday celebrated on June 19 annually. This date commemorates June 19, 1865 when a Union General read federal orders in Galveston, Texas that stated all previously enslaved people in Texas were free. This was the emancipation of the last remaining enslaved African Americans. Darkness cannot drive out darkness, only light can do that. Hate cannot drive out hate, only love can do that. Martin Luther King Jr. https://www.msdwt.k12.in.us/2020/06/no-racism-zone/

post_text: It is with great sadness we share the passing of former MSDWT Superintendent Dr. Phil McDaniel who led our schools from 1982-1993. He was a highly respected leader and a beloved member of our community. In fact, while he led MSDWT, Dr. McDaniel was bestowed the State of Indiana's highest honor, the Sagamore of the Wabash from Governor Evan Bayh in 1993. Our thoughts are with his friends and family. post_text:
Developing Readers ONE Book at a Time-ONE Partnership at a Time!

As we close this school year we are very thankful for the many community partnerships that support our mission. The Washington Township Lions Club is a PROUD partner of the Metropolitan School District of Washington Township. Committed to the development of the whole child, this spring marks the second consecutive year in which they have provided each of the 8 Elementary School Media Centers with Hoosier Book Award Winner Book Sets. These collections are made up of books for both primary and intermediate students and are comprised of books that have been selected as Hoosier Book Award Winners. Developing readers and the enthusiastic responses from the students and staff are what the Lions Club cite as the reasons they looks forward to continuing this project in the future.

Lions Club representatives recently delivered these valuable learning resources to Washington Township.
https://www.msdwt.k12.in.us/2020/05/lions-club-supports-wt/

shared_text:
Advancement Center for Washington Township Schools and North Central Alumni
May 15 at 2:13 PM 路

Washington Township Schools is lucky to have amazing educators like Joyce Click. You may have seen Joyce recognized recently in the IndyStar for reaching kids in fun and inventive ways during school closure... something we were excited to learn The Advancement Center has been able to help with!
http://indianapolisstar.in.newsmemory.com/?publink=02c95f6c0.
Adapting for zoom, she brought North Central High School alumnus, music consultant, producer, and concert pianist with a specialty in African American art forms, Joshua Thompson from Village Voices, to her students. Josh not only performed for the students, but also facilitated discussion with the students about their perceptions of classical music and the impacts from composers of color. Thank you to all of our amazing educators thinking outside of the box to engage our students right now, and to all of our donors helping them with the resources to make it happen!

shared_text:
Advancement Center for Washington Township Schools and North Central Alumni
May 4 at 12:46 PM 路

It is National Teacher Appreciation week and we are appreciating our teachers more now than ever! This time of year, we help families acknowledge their admiration for MSDWT teachers and staff through our Thank-a-Teacher program. For every Thank-A-Teacher gift (minimum of $10) received, we send a note and customized notepad to the teacher(s) classroom.

HOWEVER, this year the classroom looks different, and we decided our notepads should too!

For Teacher Appreciation 2020 we will be offering this limited edition, Quarantine Thank-a-Teacher note pad. For every Thank-A-Teacher gift (minimum of $10) we receive during the week of teacher appreciation, May 4-10, we will send an email to the nominated teacher or staff member notifying them of your gift. We will also let them know that as soon as they return to their school building, there will be a limited edition notepad waiting for them!

To participate visit: https://www.advancementcenterwts.org/online-giving-form/
and select Thank-A-Teacher from the Fund Designation drop-down menu.

post_text: The members of the Washington Township School Board were saddened to learn of the loss of one of our Washington Township family members, Coach Paul Loggan. For many decades, Coach Loggan has been a pillar to Indiana high school athletics, high school football, Washington Township Schools and North Central High School. If there was any question about any part of North Central athletics, Coach Loggan knew the answer. In addition to being a devoted husband and father to his wife and children, Coach Loggan was a dad, a mentor, a friend, teacher and coach to many students at North Central. He has followed many of his students way beyond their high school years and has been one of the most favorite visits for North Centrals alumni when they are in town or visiting North Central. He is a legend that will truly be missed, but never forgotten.

It was great seeing everyone during our parade of cars today. It was amazing to see all of the families that came out to wave and made signs. We wish we could have gotten to everyone, so we apologize to those families we didn't make it to today. We want everyone to stay safe and know that the staff at Fox Hill is thinking of you.

post_text:
March 19, 2020: **Important** UPDATED Information

On March 19, 2020, Governor Holcomb announced at a 1:00 PM press conference that all Indiana schools should remain closed until May 1, 2020 at minimum due to Coronavirus. Washington Township will be working on communications to families with details for April 6  May 1 soon. In the meantime, there are no changes to the plan for Washington Township students through April 3 that was communicated last Friday, March 13, 2020. These details are located at https://www.msdwt.k12.in.us/2020/03/march-13-covid-19-update/

Washington Township Schools will continue close collaboration with the health department and appropriate governmental agencies on this public health crisis. We encourage everyone to continue self-isolation and the guidance details from the health department.

continue reading here: https://www.msdwt.k12.in.us/2020/03/march-13-covid-19-update/

post_text: Over 40,000 meals were distributed to Washington Township families today through our curbside pick up. Thank you to all of our amazing Child Nutrition Staff, administrators, and other district volunteers for assisting today! Please remember that there are community food resources listed on the district web page https://www.msdwt.k12.in.us/2020/03/free-meal-packets/
